WEBVTT

00:28.689 --> 00:29.990
Good morning.

00:29.990 --> 00:31.225
Good morning.
Good morning.

00:31.225 --> 00:32.927
Good morning.
Good morning.

00:32.927 --> 00:36.463
For the record,
Daniel Michael Gallagher,

00:36.463 --> 00:39.099
convicted of murder
in the second degree,

00:39.099 --> 00:41.769
given a sentence
of 15 years to life.

00:42.469 --> 00:44.071
This is your first appearance

00:44.071 --> 00:45.940
before the board?
Yes, ma'am.

00:45.940 --> 00:47.975
You managed to keep
a clean disciplinary record.

00:47.975 --> 00:51.679
You were involved in the
exoneration of David Rangel?

00:51.679 --> 00:53.113
You seem
to have made it a point

00:53.113 --> 00:54.882
to provide that
kind of assistance.

00:54.882 --> 00:57.818
I agree with whoever it was that
said that the greatest threat

00:57.818 --> 01:00.621
to our system of justice
is an innocent man.

01:00.621 --> 01:02.957
And we understand you do have
a statement you've prepared.

01:02.957 --> 01:04.658
Yes, ma'am.

01:07.828 --> 01:11.866
I only wanted
to say that...

01:13.067 --> 01:14.535
...that I...

01:20.741 --> 01:23.577
That every day
that I have been in here,

01:23.577 --> 01:27.514
I have thought about
Alexandra Forrest.

01:27.514 --> 01:31.986
Because I need to make myself
understand what I did,

01:31.986 --> 01:33.754
how she died...

01:35.256 --> 01:38.125
...that I killed her...

01:38.125 --> 01:39.827
and why.

01:46.934 --> 01:50.771
My position,

01:50.771 --> 01:52.940
my accomplishments,

01:52.940 --> 01:55.943
everything that I had...

01:58.345 --> 02:01.815
...and everything
that I wanted...

02:01.815 --> 02:04.018
next to that, she meant nothing.

02:07.087 --> 02:10.891
That she tried to jeopardize it,

02:10.891 --> 02:13.594
in my mind...

02:13.594 --> 02:16.630
meant that I was justified
in whatever I chose to do.

02:17.798 --> 02:19.733
And I chose rage.

02:22.136 --> 02:24.271
I chose to lose control.

02:31.679 --> 02:33.747
I chose to take her life.

02:35.249 --> 02:37.685
And the man that I had always
believed myself to be

02:37.685 --> 02:39.653
could not have done that.

02:39.653 --> 02:41.255
But I did.

02:43.390 --> 02:46.126
So I have tried to take
every single day

02:46.126 --> 02:48.162
that I have been in here...

02:50.931 --> 02:53.867
...to come...

02:53.867 --> 02:55.035
to a better understanding

02:55.035 --> 02:57.738
of who I really am...

02:57.738 --> 02:59.239
and to atone.

03:05.346 --> 03:08.248
Um, that's all I have to say.

03:08.248 --> 03:12.786
If you were to be paroled, what
plans do you have for yourself?

03:18.892 --> 03:20.327
The first...

03:24.999 --> 03:26.667
The first thing
that I would like to do

03:26.667 --> 03:29.803
is to be reconnected
with my family.

03:29.803 --> 03:31.338
Do you have
any more questions?

03:31.338 --> 03:32.840
No.

03:32.840 --> 03:34.208
Thank you, Mr. Gallagher.

03:34.208 --> 03:36.076
We'll take all of this
under advisement

03:36.076 --> 03:38.078
and notify you
of our decision.

03:38.078 --> 03:40.180
Thank you all
very much.

03:43.183 --> 03:45.285
Come on.
Let's go.

04:16.083 --> 04:18.318
Uh, that's not mine.

04:18.318 --> 04:19.920
That's not my phone.

04:19.920 --> 04:21.188
Name?

04:21.188 --> 04:22.823
Ellen Gallagher.

04:24.925 --> 04:26.927
<i>...on vacation in
Switzerland, and, one morning,</i>

04:26.927 --> 04:29.897
<i>his wife came back from a hike
and described climbing a hill</i>

04:29.897 --> 04:31.899
<i>to find an old wooden house
at the top,</i>

04:31.899 --> 04:35.069
<i>with a beautiful
handcarved door.</i>

04:35.069 --> 04:37.337
<i>Did I not tell this story
in junior honors seminar?</i>

04:37.337 --> 04:39.339
<i>No? Okay.</i>

04:39.339 --> 04:41.075
<i>Well, so, after lunch,</i>

04:41.075 --> 04:43.110
<i>she wanted him to see
the house with the door,</i>

04:43.110 --> 04:44.778
<i>so they climbed the hill</i>

04:44.778 --> 04:46.814
<i>and then all
the surrounding hills,</i>

04:46.814 --> 04:48.782
<i>but they never found it.</i>

04:48.782 --> 04:52.252
<i>Carl Jung described his wife
as calm and rational,</i>

04:52.252 --> 04:54.154
<i>logical, impossible to fool.</i>

04:54.154 --> 04:56.790
<i>But so here was something
she swore had happened,</i>

04:56.790 --> 05:01.195
<i>that he absolutely
could not explain.</i>

05:01.195 --> 05:04.731
I mean,
four other classes, yeah,

05:04.731 --> 05:06.200
and then the reading,
as well.

05:06.200 --> 05:09.103
So it's-- it's a lot,
but, uh, I think I just find

05:09.103 --> 05:12.739
that, with, like, listening
and even taking notes,

05:12.739 --> 05:15.075
everything is just sort of gone
as soon as it's over.

05:15.075 --> 05:18.212
So doing that transcription
just really helps,

05:18.212 --> 05:20.447
like, set it in stone for me,
I guess.

05:20.447 --> 05:22.316
So it's worth
all the extra time.

05:22.316 --> 05:25.786
Plus, you'll have a hard copy of
every lecture to refer back to.

05:25.786 --> 05:27.221
Yeah.

05:29.223 --> 05:30.357
Still, though,
why are other people

05:30.357 --> 05:32.926
just, like, so good at it?
At what?

05:32.926 --> 05:35.262
Remembering
what they hear?

05:35.262 --> 05:36.530
Yeah.

05:36.530 --> 05:38.198
Trust me, they're not.

05:45.439 --> 05:46.940
So, do you--

05:46.940 --> 05:52.846
My father might be, um...

05:52.846 --> 05:54.548
up for parole.

05:58.852 --> 06:00.354
He's up for parole.

06:01.989 --> 06:05.292
That must have been so hard
for you to be holding on to.

06:05.292 --> 06:09.530
All this time, you've had to
carry his being in prison,

06:09.530 --> 06:12.799
when you had told me
he was dead.

06:15.936 --> 06:19.306
Well, he's never
e-mailed me before.

06:19.306 --> 06:20.974
Ever.

06:20.974 --> 06:23.243
And then he asked me
to come to his hearing,

06:23.243 --> 06:26.813
and I didn't e-mail back,

06:26.813 --> 06:28.582
but I went.

06:30.517 --> 06:32.052
I'm sorry that I lied.

06:35.422 --> 06:38.058
People tell me what
they're ready to tell me.

06:55.609 --> 06:57.377
Let me run something
by you, okay?

06:57.377 --> 06:59.146
Work-related?

06:59.146 --> 07:02.082
Speaking of birthdays,
it was Marlena's birthday.

07:02.082 --> 07:04.151
And she's been sending me
these screenshots

07:04.151 --> 07:06.220
of some shit
called a tennis bracelet.

07:06.220 --> 07:08.088
Like I got that kind
of scratch laying around.

07:08.088 --> 07:09.890
So I had to get creative.

07:09.890 --> 07:11.425
Oh, boy.

07:11.425 --> 07:12.993
What?
It's nothing.

07:12.993 --> 07:14.294
I just don't want to have
anything in my mouth

07:14.294 --> 07:15.529
when you tell me
what you did.

07:15.529 --> 07:17.130
So I thought to myself,

07:17.130 --> 07:18.932
"How much jewelry have I got
Winnie over the years?"

07:18.932 --> 07:21.168
And then I've never seen
most of it, like, ever again.

07:21.168 --> 07:23.403
So I looked,
and I found this one thing

07:23.403 --> 07:25.539
that pretty much solved
my problem exactly.

07:25.539 --> 07:27.174
So I repurposed it.

07:27.174 --> 07:30.277
Oh. Marlena loves it.
She went fucking crazy.

07:30.277 --> 07:32.579
I'm sure she did. You both
clearly have great taste.

07:32.579 --> 07:34.414
Fuck you, dude.
I need some advice here.

07:34.414 --> 07:36.984
Why? You already did the thing
I would have told you not to do.

07:36.984 --> 07:40.087
Because I could have sworn
that Winnie would not remember

07:40.087 --> 07:42.055
this fuckin' thing
that she's never worn once,

07:42.055 --> 07:44.224
but now she says
that she can't find it

07:44.224 --> 07:45.592
and that she thinks
someone stole it.

07:45.592 --> 07:47.294
And she wants me
to claim it on insurance.

07:47.294 --> 07:49.296
Which I have not done yet.
Because that's fraud.

07:49.296 --> 07:50.964
So I explained to her,
I was like, "Babe, look.

07:50.964 --> 07:53.300
It doesn't make sense that
a thief would just sneak in here

07:53.300 --> 07:55.235
and steal this one thing.
It probably just slipped

07:55.235 --> 07:57.271
through the cracks
in the drawer or whatever."

07:57.271 --> 07:59.673
Which, yeah, I think I might
just double down on that.

07:59.673 --> 08:01.241
Yeah, that's a good idea.

08:01.241 --> 08:03.510
Or you could blame it
on one of the kids.

08:04.645 --> 08:08.248
Frank, honestly, stop talking
to me, your direct supervisor,

08:08.248 --> 08:10.550
about your criminal
fucking enterprise.

08:10.550 --> 08:13.353
And if you come to my party with
anybody other than your wife,

08:13.353 --> 08:15.155
I will crap thunder on you.

08:15.155 --> 08:18.225
Like Marlena would want to come
to a geezer's party. She's 23.

08:19.059 --> 08:20.394
Oh, there it is, the face.

08:20.394 --> 08:23.330
You know, no wonder
they're gonna make you judge.

08:32.272 --> 08:35.275
- Well, happy birthday, Danny.
- Thank you, Terry.

08:35.275 --> 08:37.411
Also, tell me again
on Thursday.

08:42.249 --> 08:43.483
Morning.

08:43.483 --> 08:44.951
Good morning.

08:44.951 --> 08:46.253
You see the hearing's
been pushed?

08:46.253 --> 08:48.388
I did, yes, thank you.
How are you today?

08:48.388 --> 08:50.991
Okay.

08:50.991 --> 08:52.259
I had a dream last night

08:52.259 --> 08:54.494
this giant snake
bit me on the face.

08:54.494 --> 08:56.663
Well, that's disturbing.

08:58.598 --> 08:59.700
Beatrice.

08:59.700 --> 09:01.101
Oh.
Here for Koestner?

09:01.101 --> 09:02.602
Yep, it's been
a while

09:02.602 --> 09:05.172
since I've been up against
one of Norman's juries.

09:05.172 --> 09:08.141
You should be fine, so long as
you haven't missed anything.

09:08.809 --> 09:10.644
You haven't missed anything,
have you?

09:10.644 --> 09:12.412
Shut up.

09:12.412 --> 09:15.215
Ooh! Heard your 40th birthday's
coming up.

09:15.215 --> 09:17.517
That's young for a judge.

09:17.517 --> 09:19.453
Just not young
for a <i>person.</i>

09:19.453 --> 09:21.388
Damn!
Beatrice, that hurts.

09:35.268 --> 09:37.070
Hey, hey, boss. Hey.

09:37.070 --> 09:39.206
Hey.
Can I get a sign-off?

09:39.206 --> 09:42.409
Vehicular manslaughter.
I was thinking probation.

09:44.311 --> 09:46.713
Defendant blew a 1.8.
That's pretty drunk, Phil.

09:46.713 --> 09:48.248
Right, but it's
a first offense.

09:48.248 --> 09:50.117
Plus, the vic died
of a heart attack.

09:50.117 --> 09:52.319
No. No deal.
Save your empathy for somebody

09:52.319 --> 09:54.521
who doesn't get behind
the wheel shit-faced.

09:54.521 --> 09:56.189
Bad decisions lead
to bad outcomes.

09:56.189 --> 09:58.258
You play stupid games,
you win stupid prizes.

09:58.258 --> 10:00.060
How you doing, Your Honor?

10:00.060 --> 10:02.095
Don't jinx me, Gabriel.

10:10.504 --> 10:11.638
I'm home!

10:25.452 --> 10:27.320
Those are
pretty pictures.

10:27.320 --> 10:29.222
Nana got it for me.
Oh, really?

10:29.222 --> 10:30.690
At the Taschen store.

10:30.690 --> 10:32.559
It was sealed in plastic,
so it might have been

10:32.559 --> 10:35.362
the illustrated Scandinavian
Kama Sutra, for all she knew.

10:35.362 --> 10:37.531
But she liked the cover,
so here we are.

10:37.531 --> 10:40.267
But it's not, right?
Right?

10:40.267 --> 10:41.802
It's fairy tales.

10:41.802 --> 10:44.337
Fairy tales. Okay.
Fairy tales are good.

10:44.337 --> 10:46.640
We like fairy tales.
Mm-hmm.

10:59.252 --> 11:01.288
I'm sorry.

11:01.288 --> 11:02.823
Go on.

11:06.326 --> 11:10.464
I was
a complete shithead.

11:10.464 --> 11:12.332
And I'm sorry.

11:12.332 --> 11:14.301
The best was how
you literally had just said

11:14.301 --> 11:15.702
you didn't care
what we watched.

11:15.702 --> 11:17.571
It was extremely...
bag-of-dicks.

11:21.374 --> 11:25.679
You're right, I'm wrong,
I'm sorry...

11:25.679 --> 11:29.416
and I think maybe
just all the moving stuff

11:29.416 --> 11:30.851
was getting in my pocket.

11:30.851 --> 11:33.453
Wait. That was about moving?
Do you not want to move?

11:33.453 --> 11:36.122
Honey, I'm really just
trying to say I'm sorry.

11:37.390 --> 11:41.428
'Cause, you know, we can just
still flip that house instead.

11:41.428 --> 11:43.330
Just sayin'.
And while we're saying stuff,

11:43.330 --> 11:45.732
you don't have to be a judge
either if you don't want.

11:45.732 --> 11:47.734
"The hours are easier,
the schedule's more reliable,

11:47.734 --> 11:51.438
it's such an honor"--
that you can still refuse.

11:52.405 --> 11:54.574
It'd be a baller move, right?

11:54.574 --> 11:57.744
They offer it to me, and I'm
just like, "Tsk, eh, I'm good."

12:00.380 --> 12:03.149
I bet you didn't know that
judges get to go to conferences.

12:03.149 --> 12:04.784
In fancy places, no less.

12:04.784 --> 12:06.520
What kind and where?

12:06.520 --> 12:07.888
Mostly the law kind.

12:07.888 --> 12:10.390
And how about Aruba?

12:10.390 --> 12:11.758
Aruba means Milwaukee.

12:11.758 --> 12:13.660
Milwaukee means
San Bernardino.

12:13.660 --> 12:15.529
Hey, kiddo.

12:17.397 --> 12:19.165
Where do the sun
and the moon come into it?

12:19.165 --> 12:20.734
Well,
the stepmother's castle

12:20.734 --> 12:23.336
is east of the sun
and west of the moon.

12:23.336 --> 12:25.171
Ohh...

12:25.171 --> 12:26.640
Doesn't have to
have a stepmother,

12:26.640 --> 12:29.209
but when it does, man,
you know it's good, right?

12:35.348 --> 12:37.183
Hey, what's the problem
with Suarez's case?

12:37.183 --> 12:38.652
He says you're not
gonna charge it.

12:38.652 --> 12:40.453
I asked him to get
one of the four guys

12:40.453 --> 12:42.222
to flip on the other ones.
It's not a problem for me.

12:42.222 --> 12:43.723
Yeah, well,
he's already got a witness,

12:43.723 --> 12:47.394
who's a working man,
a father, community pillar.

12:47.394 --> 12:49.329
Why does he need to negotiate
with a murderer?

12:49.329 --> 12:51.565
Can you tell me where
this perfect witness
is gonna be in six months?

12:51.565 --> 12:53.867
Eating M&M's outside of
Courtroom 12 while waiting
to be called to the stand.

12:53.867 --> 12:56.202
